[2026-03-13T20:04:01Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01JbfQnuJfAarR4ZopGqCRVz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear understanding of the codebase. Let me plan the implementation:\n\n## Plan\n\n### Backend Changes\n\n1. **New endpoint `GET /api/runs/{id}/logs`** - Returns paginated log lines as JSON\n   - Query params: `offset` (line number to start from), `limit` (max lines to return)\n   - Response: `{\"lines\": [...], \"total\": N}`\n   - This reads full.log, counts total lines, returns the requested slice\n\n2. **Modify `streamFullLog`** - Accept a `tail` parameter to only send the last N lines\n   - When streaming completed runs, only send last 1000 lines\n   - Send a metadata SSE event first with `total_lines` and `skipped` count\n\n3. **Modify `handleAPIStream`** - Pass `tail` query param to `streamFullLog`\n\n### Frontend Changes\n\n4. **Modify `run_detail.html`** - \n   - Handle the `meta` SSE event to know if there are earlier lines\n   - Show a \"Load earlier logs\" button when there are skipped lines\n   - On click, fetch earlier lines via `/api/runs/{id}/logs?offset=X&limit=1000`\n   - Prepend those lines to the log viewer\n\n### Tests\n\n5. **Add tests**\n\nNow I'm thinking through the implementation. The key approach is to have `streamFullLog` count the total lines in the file first, then if it exceeds 1000, skip ahead to stream only the last 1000 lines. I'll send a metadata SSE event upfront with the total line count and how many we're skipping, so the frontend knows whether to show a \"Load earlier logs\" button. The new `/api/runs/{id}/logs` endpoint will handle fetching specific line ranges from the full.log file and returning them as JSON. For active runs using the broadcaster, I don't need to change the initial snapshot behavior since they only receive live streaming updates anyway. I should also respect a `tail` query parameter on the SSE stream endpoint to let callers customize how many lines to fetch, defaulting to 1000 if not specified.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the complexity here: the raw file lines don't map directly to visible lines because the LLM log parser filters out some protocol-only events. So I need to track which lines are actually visible after parsing, not just count raw file lines.\n\nMy approach is to have a single function that reads the full log, parses everything, and filters to only the visible lines. The SSE stream then sends the last 1000 of those, and the REST endpoint can slice into that same array. This keeps the logic consistent, though I'm aware it could be memory-intensive for very large logs—but since we're already loading the whole file for streaming anyway, it should be manageable for now.\n\nNow I'm starting to implement the handler changes...\n\nActually, I should make the tail parameter configurable via query param for flexibility, but default to 1000 lines as specified. Let me also verify what the default log type should be.\n\nNow I'm writing the function to read visible log lines... Writing the logs endpoint... Finishing up the query parameter parsing for the limit and calculating the start position, then encoding the response with the sliced log lines and metadata. Now I need to update the stream handler to pass the tail parameter through.\n\nUpdating the stream handler signature...\n\nNow for the frontend changes, I'm adding a \"Load earlier\" button above the log viewer to let users fetch older log entries.\n\nSetting up event listeners... Building the log display... Still writing button styles...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2595,"cache_read_input_tokens":39813,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2595},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"143fc353-8adb-4cb0-8d24-a68ddf79996d","uuid":"582474aa-bc22-4c75-a894-73f70a4e6c86"}
